{"schema": {"fields":[{"type":"integer","name":"index"},{"type":"string","name":"author_association"},{"type":"string","name":"body"},{"type":"datetime","name":"created_at"},{"type":"string","name":"html_url"},{"type":"integer","name":"id"},{"type":"string","name":"issue_url"},{"type":"string","name":"node_id"},{"type":"datetime","name":"updated_at"},{"type":"string","name":"url"},{"type":"string","name":"user"}],"pandas_version":"0.20.0","primaryKey":["index"]}, "data": [{"index":0,"author_association":"COLLABORATOR","body":"For related history, see the discussion in https:\/\/github.com\/mrdoob\/three.js\/pull\/7326 and https:\/\/github.com\/mrdoob\/three.js\/issues\/9387.\r\n\r\nAlso https:\/\/github.com\/mrdoob\/three.js\/commit\/8c4f342ac4b8b92877bf41f89380a5237b4effc7.\r\n\r\nLooking at this `Vector3` method...\r\n```javascript\r\nmultiplyScalar: function ( scalar ) {\r\n\r\n\tif ( isFinite( scalar ) ) {\r\n\r\n\t\tthis.x *= scalar;\r\n\t\tthis.y *= scalar;\r\n\t\tthis.z *= scalar;\r\n\r\n\t} else {\r\n\r\n\t\tthis.x = 0;\r\n\t\tthis.y = 0;\r\n\t\tthis.z = 0;\r\n\r\n\t}\r\n\r\n\treturn this;\r\n\r\n},\r\n```\r\n... in order to prevent `Infinity`, we return an incorrect answer without warning instead. I am not sure that is a good tradeoff.\r\n\r\n>Does this optimisation look good to you?\r\n\r\nAgain, returning an incorrect answer without warning if `w` is zero.\r\n\r\n\/ping @bhouston ","created_at":"2017-02-21T15:39:26.000Z","html_url":"https:\/\/github.com\/mrdoob\/three.js\/issues\/10849#issuecomment-281380368","id":281380368,"issue_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/repos\/mrdoob\/three.js\/issues\/10849","node_id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDI4MTM4MDM2OA==","updated_at":"2017-02-21T15:39:26.000Z","url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/repos\/mrdoob\/three.js\/issues\/comments\/281380368","user":{"following_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/WestLangley\/following{\/other_user}","events_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/WestLangley\/events{\/privacy}","avatar_url":"https:\/\/avatars2.githubusercontent.com\/u\/1000017?v=4","url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/WestLangley","gists_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/WestLangley\/gists{\/gist_id}","html_url":"https:\/\/github.com\/WestLangley","subscriptions_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/WestLangley\/subscriptions","node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjEwMDAwMTc=","repos_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/WestLangley\/repos","received_events_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/WestLangley\/received_events","gravatar_id":"","starred_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/WestLangley\/starred{\/owner}{\/repo}","site_admin":false,"login":"WestLangley","type":"User","id":1000017,"followers_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/WestLangley\/followers","organizations_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/WestLangley\/orgs"}},{"index":1,"author_association":"CONTRIBUTOR","body":"I agree with checking for 0 in the divide function.  I have never seen before a checking isFinite\/isNan in the multiplyScalar function, but I guess that is sort of the converse.  I think it is not necessary.  This goes against Three.JS's philosophy of not checking the validity of inputs.  A non-finite input to this function is just wrong and it is caused by a bug elsewhere.  I figure we do not have to protect against it.\r\n\r\nThe protecting against a divide by 0 in the divide function is much more common, so I would leave that one.  I  guess I am inconsistent in my reasoning but I am favoring protecting us from the very common error of dividing by zero and less worried about this particular case.  I think these choices are also very common in other 3D libraries.\r\n\r\nOnce we decide to protect against non-finite values, we really should be checking for them almost everywhere for consistently sake -- but we we are not likely to do so, so why check in this function?","created_at":"2017-02-21T16:08:23.000Z","html_url":"https:\/\/github.com\/mrdoob\/three.js\/issues\/10849#issuecomment-281389762","id"